TheNexuStore — E-commerce Architecture & Delivery Guide (v1.1)
Client/Owner: NEXUS SP Solutions
Project: New e-commerce platform “TheNexuStore” (replacement of current Odoo-based store)
Audience: Suraj, Chaitayna (Full-Stack Developers)
Supervisor: Antonio (NEXUS IT/Cyber)
Priorities: Clean architecture, stability, speed, conversion, scalability, maintainability

1) Context and Purpose

We are rebuilding our e-commerce because the current implementation (Odoo + custom API) has accumulated technical debt, is difficult to evolve, and has reliability issues. The new store must be designed as a modern, scalable e-commerce platform, with robust supplier integration starting with INFORTISA, and extendable to future suppliers.
We want the result to be:
Modular (clear boundaries; replaceable components)
API-First (same backend for web, future mobile app, and internal admin platform)
Scalable (more suppliers, more traffic, more categories)
Understandable (clean codebase, documentation, testing, monitoring)
Operationally complete (checkout → payment → invoice → shipping/tracking → emails → returns/RMA)

2) Goals and Non-Goals
2.1 Goals
Launch a stable, high-converting e-commerce similar in UX to PCComponentes/Design by Sai.
API-first architecture that supports: Web storefront, future mobile app (iOS/Android), and an internal operations/admin console (“simple multi-platform”).
Integrate INFORTISA first, using a scalable “supplier adapter” approach.
Automate the full order lifecycle: Cart → Checkout → Payment → Invoice generation → Shipment/tracking → Customer notifications.
Strong SEO foundation and high performance (mobile-first, Core Web Vitals oriented).
Proper DevOps: staging, CI/CD, backups, monitoring, and security controls.
2.2 Non-Goals for MVP (Phase 1)
Full marketplace / multi-vendor system.
Replacing full accounting/ERP processes (we will export data cleanly).
Building an overly complex custom CMS from scratch.

3) Recommended Target Architecture (High-Level)
3.1 Strong Recommendation: Headless/Composable Commerce
We want to decouple the storefront from the commerce core. WordPress can be used for marketing content, but catalog + checkout + orders must be controlled by the commerce backend to keep integration and operations stable.
3.2 Components Overview
Storefront Web (Front): Next.js (React) for performance + SEO + scalability.
CMS (optional): WordPress Headless (only for pages/blog/landing content).
Commerce Core (Back): Node.js NestJS (preferred) or equivalent. Must expose OpenAPI/Swagger.
Database: PostgreSQL (primary).
Cache: Redis (sessions, caching, rate limiting).
Search: OpenSearch/Elasticsearch (self-host) or Algolia (SaaS).
Async/Queue: RabbitMQ (self-host) or AWS SQS for imports, invoices, emails.
Object storage: S3/MinIO for images and documents; CDN recommended.
Observability: centralized logs + metrics dashboards + Sentry.
3.3 Environments (Mandatory)
DEV: local docker compose.
STAGING: mirrors PROD, used for validation.
PROD: hardened, backups, least-privilege access.
Important
No direct development on PROD. Fixes go through PR → staging → production.

4) Domain Model (Core Data)
4.1 Core Entities
Catalog: Product, Variant/SKU, Brand, Category, Attribute/Feature (normalized), Media (images), Documents (datasheets).
Suppliers: Supplier (INFORTISA, etc.), SupplierProduct mapping, SupplierStock, SupplierCostPrice.
Customers: Customer, Address, Company/VAT info, GDPR consent flags.
Commerce: Cart, Order, PaymentAttempt, Invoice (PDF reference), Shipment, TrackingEvent.
After-sales: Return/RMA, Refund (Support tickets optional Phase 2).
4.2 Source of Truth
Commerce Core DB is the source of truth for catalog (normalized), orders, customers.
Supplier feeds are imported and transformed into canonical model; do not depend live on supplier at request time.

5) Supplier Integration (INFORTISA First) — Adapter Pattern
5.1 Non-Negotiable: Supplier Adapters
Each supplier is a pluggable module implementing a common interface:
fetchCatalog(), fetchStock(), fetchPrices(), fetchImages(), submitOrder(), fetchTracking().
All adapters output a canonical internal schema.
5.2 Import Pipeline (Async)
Pull feed from INFORTISA (API/FTP/CSV/JSON depending on their spec).
Store raw snapshot (audit + rollback).
Transform → canonical schema (category mapping, brand normalization).
Upsert into core tables (products, attributes, media).
Compute final sale price (pricing rules).
Update search index.
Generate import report (new/changed items, missing images, failures, retries).
5.3 Stock Policy
Refresh stock frequently (example every 15–30 minutes).
Use conservative availability to prevent overselling.
Support reserved stock for carts/orders.
5.4 Pricing Rules (Configurable)
Base margin per category/brand.
Floor price protection (cost + fees + minimum profit).
Rounding rules (.99, etc.).
Promotions: coupons, time-boxed offers.
Regional tax logic configurable if needed (Ceuta vs Peninsula).

6) UX/UI Requirements (Benchmark: PCComponentes)
6.1 Navigation and Discovery
Mega-menu categories + featured brands.
Search with autosuggest (products/brands/categories).
Filters on PLP: price, brand, key specs, availability/shipping time.
Breadcrumbs and SEO-friendly slugs.
6.2 Product Detail Page (PDP)
Above the fold: name, image gallery (zoom), price, availability, shipping estimate, add-to-cart.
Trust elements: warranty/returns, secure payment badges.
Normalized specs table.
Related products: alternatives + accessories.
Documents: datasheet/manual.
SEO structured data (JSON-LD).
6.3 Checkout (Conversion Critical)
Guest checkout + account checkout.
Clear shipping costs + ETA.
Invoice details (company name, VAT ID).
Card payments (Redsys or Stripe) — decide quickly.
Confirmation page + immediate email confirmation.
6.4 Customer Account
Order history.
Invoice downloads.
Tracking status.
Returns/RMA request (simple MVP).

7) End-to-End E-commerce Flows
7.1 Standard Order Flow (Happy Path)
Customer adds items → cart.
Checkout (address + shipping + payment).
Payment success → create Order = “Paid”.
Trigger invoice generation job (PDF + store) + notification email.
Fulfillment: internal stock pick OR supplier dropship.
Shipment created + tracking recorded.
Emails: order confirmation, invoice available, shipped + tracking, delivered (optional).
7.2 Mixed Fulfillment
One order may split: items from INFORTISA and items from internal stock.
Phase 2: multiple suppliers.
7.3 Returns/RMA (MVP)
Customer selects order item → reason → request type (refund/replace).
Generate RMA number + instructions email.
Admin approves/rejects and triggers refund workflow.

8) API Design (Public + Internal)
8.1 Principles
Versioned API: /api/v1/…
OpenAPI/Swagger always up to date.
Idempotency for checkout/payment endpoints.
Webhooks for async updates (shipment updates, refunds).
Rate limiting and proper authentication scopes.
8.2 Minimum Endpoints (MVP)
Catalog: GET /products, GET /products/{id}, GET /categories, GET /brands, GET /search?q=
Cart & Checkout: POST /cart, PATCH /cart, POST /checkout, POST /payments, POST /webhooks/payment
Orders: GET /orders, GET /orders/{id}, GET /orders/{id}/invoice
Returns: POST /returns
Admin: POST /admin/imports/run, GET /admin/imports/report, GET/PUT /admin/pricing-rules, POST /admin/shipment
8.3 Authentication
Customers: JWT or session cookies (httpOnly cookies preferred).
Admin: MFA recommended; RBAC roles (admin, ops, marketing).
Service-to-service: signed tokens or mTLS.

9) Emails, Invoices, and Documents
9.1 Transactional Emails (MVP)
Order confirmation.
Payment confirmation.
Invoice available.
Shipment + tracking.
RMA updates.
Email Requirements
Template-driven (EN/ES ready), deliverability controls (SPF/DKIM/DMARC), and reliable provider recommended.
9.2 Invoice Generation
Auto-generate PDF invoice after payment confirmation.
Store PDF securely and allow download in customer account.
Export accounting data (CSV/JSON) for external accountant/gestoría.

10) Internal Admin / Operations Console (Simple Multi-Platform)
Purpose
We need a lightweight internal console so operations do not depend on developers.
MVP Admin Features
Dashboard: orders today, revenue, conversion, stock alerts.
Catalog management: category mapping, override descriptions, manage featured products.
Pricing rules: margins per category/brand, promotions, coupons.
Imports: run imports, view status/report, retry failed jobs.
Orders: change status, attach tracking, handle cancellations/refunds.
Returns: approve/reject RMA.

11) Engineering Standards (Non-Negotiable)
11.1 Repo Structure
Monorepo recommended: /apps/storefront, /apps/admin, /services/commerce-core, /services/import-workers, /packages/shared.
Keep shared types/utilities in /packages/shared.
11.2 Branching & Releases
main = production, develop = staging, feature/* = PR only.
No direct commits to main.
Code review required.
11.3 Quality Gates
Unit tests: pricing rules, import transforms.
Integration tests: checkout/payment endpoints.
Lint + format (ESLint/Prettier).
Dependency security scanning.
Performance budget for storefront pages.
11.4 Observability
Structured logging (JSON).
Sentry (frontend + backend).
Metrics dashboards.
Alerts: import failures, payment failure spikes, supplier order submission failures, API latency.

12) Security and Compliance
Requirements
GDPR: consent records + data export/delete workflow.
Least privilege access per environment.
Secrets management (never in git).
Backups: daily DB + object storage backups; tested restore procedure.
WAF/CDN recommended on production; rate limits on auth/checkout endpoints.

13) MVP Scope (Phase 1) vs Phase 2
13.1 Phase 1 (MVP Launch)
Storefront: home, PLP, PDP, search, cart, checkout, account.
INFORTISA: import catalog/stock/price/images + reporting.
Payment: card (Redsys or Stripe).
Invoices: PDF generation + download.
Shipping: manual tracking entry in admin (MVP).
Admin: orders, imports, pricing rules.
13.2 Phase 2
Add more wholesalers via adapters.
Advanced promotions, bundles, accessories automation.
Carrier APIs (MRW/SEUR/Correos) end-to-end.
More robust returns automation.
Mobile app (reuse the same API).

